Overview

The midterm attempts to bring together everything you have learned to date. Youâll be asked to replicate a series of graphics to demonstrate your skills and provide short descriptions/explanations regarding issues and concepts in ggplot2.

You are free to use any resource at your disposal such as notes, past labs, the internet, fellow students, instructor, TA, etc. However, do not simply copy and paste solutions. This is a chance for you to assess how much you have learned and determine if you are developing practical data visualization skills and knowledge.

Datasets

The datasets used for this dataset are stephen_curry_shotdata_2023_24.txt, ga_election_data.csv, and ga_map.rda. We will also need the nbahalfcourt.jpg image.

Below you can find a short description of the variables contained in stephen_curry_shotdata_2023_24.txt:

  • GAME_ID - Unique ID for each game during the season
  • HOME - Indicates if game is "Home" or "Away"
  • PLAYER_ID - Unique player ID
  • PLAYER_NAME - Playerâs name
  • TEAM_ID - Unique team ID
  • TEAM_NAME - Team name
  • PERIOD - Quarter or period of the game
  • MINUTES_REMAINING - Minutes remaining in quarter/period
  • SECONDS_REMAINING - Seconds remaining in quarter/period
  • EVENT_TYPE - Missed Shot or Made Shot
  • SHOT_DISTANCE - Shot distance in feet
  • LOC_X - X location of shot attempt according to tracking system
  • LOC_Y - Y location of shot attempt according to tracking system

The ga_election_data.csv dataset contains the state of Georgiaâs county level results for the 2020 US presidential election. Here is a short description of the variables it contains:

  • County - name of county in Georgia
  • Candidate - name of candidate on the ballot,
  • Election Day Votes - number of votes cast on election day for a candidate within a county
  • Absentee by Mail Votes - number of votes cast absentee by mail, pre-election day, for a candidate within a county
  • Advanced Voting Votes - number of votes cast in-person, pre-election day, for a candidate within a county
  • Provisional Votes - number of votes cast on election day for a candidate within a county needing voter eligibility verification
  • Total Votes - total number of votes for a candidate within a county

We have also included the map data for Georgia (ga_map.rda) which was retrieved using tigris::counties().

Exercise 1

Using the stephen_curry_shotdata_2023_24.txt dataset replicate, as close as possible, the graphics below. After replicating the graphics provide a summary of what the graphics indicate about Stephen Curryâs shot selection such as distance from hoop, shot make/miss rate, how do makes and misses compare across distance and game time (i.e.Â across quarters/periods).

Plot 1

Hints:

  • Figure width 6 inches and height 4 inches, which is taken care of in code chunk yaml with fig-width and fig-height
  • Use minimal theme and adjust from there
  • Useful hex colors: "#1D428A" and "#FFC72C80"

Solution 
# data prep
steph_data <- steph_data |>
  mutate(
    PERIOD = if_else(PERIOD > 5, 5, PERIOD),
    PERIOD = factor(
      PERIOD,
      levels = c(1, 2, 3, 4, 5),
      labels = c("Q1", "Q2", "Q3", "Q4", "OTs")
    )
  ) |> 
  filter(SHOT_DISTANCE < 47)

# Create the shot plot
ggplot(steph_data, aes(PERIOD, SHOT_DISTANCE)) +
  geom_boxplot(varwidth = TRUE, fill = "#FFC72C80", color = "#1D428A") + # Adjust colors of box plot
  theme_minimal() +
  facet_wrap(~EVENT_TYPE, nrow = 1) + # Create two diff plots based on made/missed shot
  # Add and adjust labels 
  labs(x = "Quarter/Period", y = NULL) +
  ggtitle("Stephen Curry", subtitle = "2023-2024") +
  theme(axis.title.x = element_text(face="bold", size = 12)) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 16)) +
  theme(plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 14)) +
  theme(strip.text.x = element_text(face = "bold", size = 12)) +
  # Change scaling of y axis
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 40, 10),
                     labels = scales::label_number(suffix = " ft")) +
  # Get rid of unnecessary grid lines
  theme(panel.grid.minor = element_blank()) +
  theme(panel.grid.major.x = element_blank())

Solution 
# Create the density plot
ggplot(steph_data, aes(x = SHOT_DISTANCE)) +
  geom_density(aes(color = EVENT_TYPE, fill = EVENT_TYPE, lty = EVENT_TYPE),
               alpha = 0.25, 
               show.legend = FALSE) +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(x = NULL, y = NULL) + # Get rid of axis labels
  # Add and adjust title/subtitle
  ggtitle("Stephen Curry", subtitle = "Shot Densities (2023-2024)") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 16)) +
  theme(plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 14)) +
  # Adjust scaling of x axis
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 40, 10),
                     labels = scales::label_number(suffix = " ft")) +
  # Get rid of extra space under x-axis
  scale_y_continuous(labels = NULL, expand = c(0, 0)) +
  # Get rid of unnecessary grid lines
  theme(panel.grid.minor = element_blank()) +
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank()) +
  # Adjust colors/borders used
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#5D3A9B", "#E66100")) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("#5D3A9B", "#E66100")) +
  scale_linetype_manual(values = c("solid", 22)) +
  # Add labels for made/missed shots
  annotate("text",
          x = 4.5, y = 0.035,
          label = "Made Shots",
          hjust = -0.05, vjust = 0.25,  
          color = "#5D3A9B",
          size = 3.5) +
  annotate("text",
          x = 27.5, y = 0.081,
          label = "Missed Shots",
          hjust = -0.015, vjust = 0,  
          color = "#E66100",
          size = 3.5)

Plot 3

Hints:

  • Figure width 7 inches and height 7 inches, which is taken care of in code chunk yaml with fig-width and fig-height
  • Colors used: "grey", "red", "orange" "yellow" (donât have to use "orange", you can get away with using only "red" and "yellow")
  • To set 15+ as the highest value, you need to set the limits in the appropriate scale while also setting the na.value to the top color
  • While the plot needs to be very close to the one shown it does not need to be exact in terms of values. If you want to make it exact here are some useful values used, sometimes repeatedly, to make the plot: 0, 0.7, 5, 12, 14, 15, 16, 20
Solution 
# importing image of NBA half court
court <- grid::rasterGrob(
  jpeg::readJPEG(
    source = "data/nbahalfcourt.jpg"),
  width = unit(1, "npc"), 
  height = unit(1, "npc")
)

# plot
ggplot(steph_data, aes(x = LOC_X, y = LOC_Y)) +
  annotation_custom(
    grob = court,
    xmin = -25, xmax = 25,
    ymin = 0, ymax = 47
  ) +
  coord_fixed(expand = FALSE) +
  xlim(-25, 25) +
  ylim(0, 47) +
  # Create the hex bin plot
  stat_binhex(color = "gray", bins = 20, alpha = 0.7) +
  # Add the color gradient
  scale_fill_gradientn("Shot\nAttempts",
                       colors = c("yellow", "orange", "red"), 
                       na.value = "red", 
                       breaks = c(0, 5, 10, 15),
                       limits = c(0, 15),
                       labels = c("0", "5", "10", "15+")) + # Change the scale on the right
  labs(x = NULL, y = NULL, color = NULL) + # Get rid of unneeded labels
  # Add and adjust the title/subtitle
  ggtitle("Stephen Curry", subtitle = "Shot Chart (2023-2024)") +
  theme_void() +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 16)) +
  theme(plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 14)) +
  # Add extra space between edge of court image and legend
  theme(legend.box.spacing = unit(0.2, "in"))

Summary

Provide a summary of what the graphics above indicate about Stephen Curryâs shot selection such as distance from hoop, shot make/miss rate, how do makes and misses compare across distance and game time (i.e.Â across quarters/periods).

Solution

From the boxplot, we can tell that Steph Curry tends to take longer shots towards the start (especially) and towards the end of games. The 75th percentile for distance tends to be pretty much the same across all quarters, no matter if the shot is made or missed. Thus, when it comes to longer shots, Curry does not seem to vary too much in accuracy across quarters. Based on the width of the plots, Curry also appears to have more missed shots in the 2nd half compared to in the 1st half. From the density plot, we can see that there is a small hump for distances close to the basket, followed by a sort of plateau between 10 and 20 feet, and then a big hump between 20 and 30 feet that peaks somewhere around 26 feet. This is consistent with the âgame theoryâ approach to basketball that has exploded in recent years and been propagated by coaches like Nate Oats. Layups, depicted by the small hump, are optimal because they are high-percentage (as demonstrated by how the make hump is bigger than the miss hump there). Beyond that, mid-range shots are less optimal because they are farther away (and thus harder to make) and earn the same number of points as a layup. However, even though 3 pointers are slightly harder to make than mid-range shots (the decreasing trend of accuracy can be seen in the density plot), they earn an extra point and are thus optimal as well. However, the farther back you get behind the 3-point line, the less optimal the shots are. Thus, Curry does not attempt many shots beyond 30 feet. It makes sense that Curry, one of the most prolific 3-point shooters of all time, attempts many shots from behind the arc given that he makes them more consistently than almost anyone else in the NBA. This idea that Curry takes many layups and short 3 pointers but not as many mid-range shots or long 3 pointers is backed up by where the red (highest) shading is located in the last plot.

Exercise 2

Using the ga_election_data.csv dataset in conjunction with mapping data ga_map.rda replicate, as close as possible, the graphic below. Note the graphic is comprised of two plots displayed side-by-side. The plots both use the same shading scheme (i.e.Â scale limits and fill options).

Background Information

Holding the 2020 US Presidential election during the COVID-19 pandemic was a massive logistical undertaking. Additional voter engagement was extremely historically high. Voting operations, headed by states, ran very smoothly and encountered few COVID-19 related issues. The state of Georgia did a particularly good job at this by encouraging their residents to use early voting. About 75% of the vote in a typical county voted early! Statewide, about 80% or 4 in every 5 voters in Georgia voted early.

While it is clear that early voting was the preferred option for Georgia voters, we want to investigate whether or not voters for one candidate/party utilized early voting more than the other â we are focusing on the two major candidates/parties. We created the graphic below to explore the relationship of voting modality and voter preference, which you are tasked with recreating.

Hints:

  • Figure width 7 inches and height 7 inches, which is taken care of in code chunk yaml with fig-width and fig-height
  • Make two plots, then arrange plots accordingly using patchwork package
  • patchwork::plot_annotation() will be useful for adding graphic title and caption; youâll also set the theme options for the graphic title and caption (think font size and face) â code has been provided
  • ggthemes::theme_map() was used as the base theme for the plots
  • scale_*_gradient2() will be helpful
  • Useful hex colors: "#5D3A9B" and "#1AFF1A"
  • While the plot needs to be very close to the one shown it does not need to be exact in terms of values. If you want to make it exact here are some useful values used, sometimes repeatedly, to make the plot: 0.5, 0.75, 1, 10, 12, 14, 24

Plot

Solution 
# data
  # Changed variable names manually to eliminate spaces
ga_graph <- ga_election_dat |> 
  # Add a new variable that determines the percentage of votes completed by mail-in
  mutate(
    prop_pre_eday = (Absentee_by_Mail_Votes + Advanced_Voting_Votes) / Total_Votes
  ) |> 
  # Get rid of the columns with _vote in the name of the column
  select(-contains("_vote")) 

# Biden map data
biden_map_data <- ga_map |> 
  # Keep all rows where the candidate voted for was Joe Biden
  left_join(
    ga_graph |> 
      filter(Candidate == "Joseph R. Biden"),
    by = c(name = "County")
  )

# trump map data
trump_map_data <- ga_map |> 
  # Keep all rows where the candidate voted for was Donald Trump
  left_join(
    ga_graph |> 
      filter(Candidate == "Donald J. Trump"),
    by = c(name ="County")
  )

# Biden plot
biden_plot <- ggplot(biden_map_data, aes(fill = prop_pre_eday)) +
  geom_sf() +
  theme_map() + 
  # Fill in the map on a gradient based on proportion of votes that were mail-in
  scale_fill_gradientn(name = NULL,
                       colors = c("#1AFF1A", "white", "#5D3A9B"),
                       na.value = "grey100",
                       limits = c(0.50, 1.00), # Gradient should go from 50% to 100%
                       guide = "none") + # Eliminate legend
  # Add/adjust title/subtitle of graph
  ggtitle("Joseph R. Biden", subtitle = "Democratic Nominee") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 14)) +
  theme(plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 12))

# Trump plot
trump_plot <- ggplot(trump_map_data, aes(fill = prop_pre_eday)) +
  geom_sf() +
  theme_map() +
  # Fill in the map on a gradient based on proportion of votes that were mail-in
  scale_fill_gradientn(name = NULL,
                       colors = c("#1AFF1A", "white", "#5D3A9B"),
                       na.value = "grey100",
                       breaks = c(0.50, 0.75, 1.00), # Change which numbers appear in legend
                       limits = c(0.50, 1.00), # Gradient should go from 50% to 100%
                       labels = c("50%", "75%", "100%")) + # Change legend labels
  # Add/adjust title/subtitle of graph
  ggtitle("Donald J. Trump", subtitle = "Republican Nominee") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 14)) +
  theme(plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 12)) +
  # Change legend position and text size to match example
  theme(legend.position = c(0.78, 0.82)) +
  theme(legend.text = element_text(size = 10))

# Final plot
biden_plot + trump_plot +
  # Add title and caption to combined plot and adjust their boldness/text size
  plot_annotation(title = "Percentage of votes from early voting",
                  caption = "Georgia: 2020 US Presidential Election Results",
                  theme = theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 24, face = "bold")) +
                          theme(plot.caption = element_text(size = 10)))

Summary

Provide a summary of how the two maps relate to one another. That is, what insight can we learn from the graphic.

Solution

From the maps, we can see that the general trend is that fewer Trump voters voted early by mail than did Biden voters. Still, however, we can see that every county did have a majority of voters for each candidate vote by mail. We can also see that voting by mail was completed by more than 75% of voters for each candidate voted by mail in the Atlanta area. Voting by mail seemed to be more common in the northern half and Atlantic shore of the state than in other parts.

Exercise 3

One thing that makes using ggplot2 in R so powerful is the ever expanding set of extension packages. At this point, students should have the skills and know how to be able to make use of extension packages. The focus of this exercise is for students to demonstrate their ability to make use of a ggplot2 extension package.

For this exercise you will need the penguins dataset from the palmerpenguins package. The extension package is ggside. A little internet searching and you should be able to find the documentation for ggside and its GitHub` repo with very useful examples.

Recreate the graphic below as closely as possible

Hints:

  • alpha values: 0.6 and 0.3
  • scale for the side panels: 0.3
  • should be able to track down an example that is very similar to this
Solution 
# Load the palmerpenguins and ggside packages
#install.packages("palmerpenguins")
library(ggside)
library(palmerpenguins)

# Extract the penguins data from palmerpenguins
penguins <- penguins

# Create the main plot
main_plot <- ggplot(data = penguins, aes(x = flipper_length_mm, y = body_mass_g)) +
  theme_minimal() +
  geom_point(aes(color = species), alpha = 0.6, size = 1.8)

# Patch the plots together
main_plot + geom_xsidedensity(aes(fill = species), # Create density plot on top
                              alpha = 0.3,
                              position = "stack") + # Each color stacked on top of each other
  # Change scale of top panel
  theme(ggside.panel.scale.x = 0.3) +
  # Create histogram to the right
  geom_ysideboxplot(aes(x = species, fill = species),
                    orientation = "x", # Change orientation from horizontal to vertical
                    show.legend = FALSE) +
  # Change scale of right panel
  theme(ggside.panel.scale.y = 0.3) +
  # Adjust text labels
  labs(x = "Flipper Length (mm)", y = "Body Mass (grams)") +
  scale_ysidex_discrete(guide = guide_axis(angle = 45)) +
  theme(legend.position = "none")
